{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1a8cd646-3171-49b8-94dd-048ca1a83b7b","content":"The template has all the **required** fields (`identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `classifications`, `tags`), but there are a few issues before it's publish-ready:\n\n**Blockers:**\n\n1. **Missing `description`** — NuGet packages without a description have poor discoverability and some tooling warns about it.\n2. **`Framework` symbol has no `replaces`** — The parameter exists but won't substitute anything in the output files. You likely need `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or a matching token) so the chosen framework actually gets applied.\n\n**Recommended additions:**\n\n3. **No `$schema`** — Adding `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` enables editor validation/IntelliSense.\n4. **No `groupIdentity`** — Useful for grouping related templates in a pack (e.g., `\"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n5. **No `preferNameDirectory`** — Typically `true` for project templates so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory.\n6. **No `defaultName`** — Controls the fallback project name when `-n` is omitted.\n\n**Verdict:** Not quite ready. At minimum, add a `description` and wire up the `Framework` symbol with `replaces` so it's functional.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4586c184-b1ba-4fdd-9916-f0f1390c9aee","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can spot:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for validation and editor support. The standard value is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet package templates so related templates can be grouped.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template exist.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n\n\n5. **`defaultValue` for Framework is \"net9.0\"** — The real problem here is the missing `replaces` property on the symbol, which means the Framework value won't actually substitute into the template files. That's a functional issue that needs fixing.\n\n6. **Missing `description`** — Important for NuGet discoverability.\n\n7. **Missing `defaultName`** — Needed to specify what the project is called if no name is provided.\n\nLooking at the required fields, I have `author`, `classifications`, and `identity` covered, but there are still gaps that would affect how this template functions in practice.\n\nThe most critical issues blocking publication are the missing `description` for NuGet visibility and the Framework symbol lacking a `replaces` property, which means selecting a framework won't actually change anything in the generated project.","outputTokens":821,"requestId":"AC32:41344:12AD03:1751D9:69F54B91"},"id":"762afe5e-ab97-48d1-b08d-01d3dc1cb309","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:56:01.952Z","parentId":"4eff5c0d-4d45-49f7-9e43-302f2d78c7ae"}
